%I A063785 #20 Mar 10 2026 23:50:31
%S A063785 20,104,464,1952,4030,5830,130304,522752,1848964,8382464,134193152
%N A063785 Numbers k such that sigma(k) = 2k + omega(k), where omega(k) is the number of distinct prime divisors of k.
%C A063785 It is easily proved that if 2^m-3 is prime then 2^(m-1)*(2^m-3) is in the sequence. - _Farideh Firoozbakht_, Feb 12 2008
%C A063785 No other terms up to 5*10^9. - _Michel Marcus_, Mar 10 2026
%o A063785 (PARI) for(n=1,10^8, if(sigma(n)==2*n+omega(n), print1(n, ", ")))
%o A063785 (PARI) isok(k) = my(f=factor(k)); sigma(f)==2*k+omega(k); \\ _Michel Marcus_, Mar 10 2026
%Y A063785 Cf. A000203, A001221, A045768, A392668.
%K A063785 nonn,more,changed
%O A063785 1,1
%A A063785 _Jason Earls_, Aug 17 2001
